    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. and for the second and third coats, do i use the same setting compound or should i switch to a pre-mixed stuff? also i noticed some tiny cracks or gaps forming in the corners where the walls meet, should i be worried about those?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For the subsequent coats, you can generally stick with the setting-type compound, but using a lightweight all-purpose joint compound for the second and third coats can make feathering easier and reduce weight. Those tiny cracks in the corners are common, and you should treat them just like the seams—apply a thin bead of joint compound, smooth it out with a taping knife, and let it dry before continuing. Don't fret about them; they are easily repaired with the same careful taping and mudding technique you are already learning.",
      "source": "target",
